                <head ana="#head_untitled-inferred-from-chapter-head">[Norway.]</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<date
                            ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-volume-rules" calendar="gregorian"
                            notAfter="1873-12-01T23:59:59-04:56"
                            notBefore="1873-01-01T00:00:00-04:56">undated</date>.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>By the Norwegian military law of 1857 “foreigners who have acquired a fast
                    domicilium in the country” are rendered liable to military duty.<note n="3"
                        xml:id="d262fn3">Mr. Crowe, Nos. 48 and 49; November 2, 1861. Mr. Crowe, No.
                        2: March 15, 1862.</note>
                </p>
                <p>A case occurred in 1861 in which Mr. Walter Foreman claimed British protection
                    against the conscription, and he was advised to try the question before the
                    Supreme Court as provided by the law of 1857.</p>
                <p>If a convention existed British subjects would be exempt by the express terms of
                    the law; but in the absence of such a convention they could only appeal to the
                    principles of equity, and ask for exemption on the ground that Norwegians were
                    not subjected to any such military service in England.</p>
            </div>
